---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Container from "@/components/layout/Container.astro";
import SectionHeading from "@/components/ui/SectionHeading.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Colophon | Dale Rogers Design"
  description="Details about the design and development of the Dale Rogers Design website."
>
  <Container>
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-20">
      <SectionHeading
        heading="Colophon"
        subheading="Last Updated: 10/11/2023"
        alignment="left"
      />

      <div class="prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert mt-10">
        <section class="mb-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">About This Site</h2>
          <p>
            Want to take a look under the hood of this website? Wonder no more!
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Technology Stack</h2>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-6 mb-4">
            <li>
              <strong>Framework:</strong> Built with <a
                href="https://astro.build">Astro</a
              >, a modern static site generator that delivers lightning-fast
              performance. I chose Astro over WordPress as it provides better
              performance and security for a portfolio site.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Styling:</strong>
              <a href="https://tailwindcss.com">Tailwind CSS</a> for utility-first
              styling and consistent design
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Typography:</strong> Custom font stack using system fonts for
              optimal performance
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Icons:</strong> Custom SVG icon system for crisp, scalable
              graphics
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Contact Form:</strong> Server-side email handling using <a
                href="https://nodemailer.com">Nodemailer</a
              > with Gmail SMTP
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Hosting</h2>
          <p>
            This site is hosted by <a href="https://crazydomains.com.au"
              >CrazyDomains</a
            > using their Linux hosting package. Since moving to Astro, the site
            is now statically generated and deployed, making it faster and more secure
            than the previous PHP-based setup. The contact form is handled server-side
            using <a href="https://nodejs.org">Node.js</a>, allowing for
            seamless email integration while maintaining the site's performance.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Development Tools</h2>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-6 mb-4">
            <li>
              <strong>Version Control:</strong>
              <a href="https://git-scm.com">Git</a> for source control management
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Code Quality:</strong>
              <a href="https://eslint.org">ESLint</a> and <a
                href="https://prettier.io">Prettier</a
              > for consistent code style
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Development:</strong>
              <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com">VS Code</a> with custom extensions
              for enhanced productivity
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Deployment:</strong> Automated deployment pipeline for seamless
              updates
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Design Tools</h2>
          <p>
            I swapped out the Adobe Creative Suite two years ago because I
            wasn't happy with the continuous and ongoing subscription fees. I
            now use <a href="https://affinity.serif.com/designer"
              >Affinity Designer</a
            > and <a href="https://affinity.serif.com/photo">Affinity Photo</a> for
            all my image editing needs. I'm also a big fan of <a
              href="https://www.omnigroup.com/omnigraffle">OmniGraffle</a
            > when creating design artefacts. Finally, I must attribute <a
              href="https://thenounproject.com">the noun project</a
            >; it is a never-ending source of inspiration and procrastination.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Design Principles</h2>
          <ul class="list-disc ml-6 mb-4">
            <li>
              <strong>Accessibility:</strong>
              <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/standards-guidelines/wcag/"
                >WCAG 2.1</a
              > guidelines followed for inclusive design
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Performance:</strong> Optimized assets and minimal JavaScript
              for fast loading
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Responsive:</strong> Mobile-first approach ensuring great experience
              on all devices
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Dark Mode:</strong> Carefully crafted dark theme for reduced
              eye strain
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Web Analytics</h2>
          <p>
            I use <a href="https://umami.is">Umami Analytics</a> to check if my mum
            has visited the site lately. It's a privacy-focused, open-source alternative
            to Google Analytics that I self-host alongside the website. No cookies,
            no personal data collection, just simple, ethical analytics.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Open Source</h2>
          <p>
            This site's source code is available on <a
              href="https://github.com/dale-rogers/dale-rogers-portfolio"
              >GitHub</a
            >. Feel free to explore how it's built or use it as inspiration for
            your own projects.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Container>
</BaseLayout>
